  "source": "Pediatrics_Nelson_textbook_data.txt - Psychological or emotional abuse involves a repeated pattern of caregiver behavior that conveys to children that they are worthless, flawed, unloved, unwanted, endangered, or only of value in meeting another's needs. Forms of emotional abuse include spurning (belittling, degrading, rejecting), terrorizing (threatening harm), exploiting/corrupting (modeling antisocial behavior), denying emotional responsiveness (ignoring, failing to express affection), isolating (confining, placing unreasonable limitations), and mental health/medical/educational neglect (refusing or failing to provide necessary treatment). Signs and symptoms of emotional abuse may include anxiety, depression, withdrawal, fearfulness, low self-esteem, decline in school performance, sleep disturbances, and age-inappropriate behaviors. While emotional abuse may occur alone, it commonly accompanies other forms of maltreatment and amplifies their negative effects. The diagnosis relies on careful observation of parent-child interactions, a comprehensive assessment of the child's functioning across multiple domains, and collateral information from schools and other caregivers. The long-term consequences of emotional abuse can be as severe as those of other forms of maltreatment, including increased risk for psychiatric disorders, substance abuse, and relationship difficulties.",
